00:21:56.000 --> 00:22:00.760
So one of the other features
that we launched-- that was

00:22:00.760 --> 00:22:03.690
actually a month ago--

00:22:03.690 --> 00:22:05.270
it was actually two features.

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:11.270
We really wanted to allow
applications to write data

00:22:11.270 --> 00:22:13.310
they have complete
control over.

00:22:13.310 --> 00:22:15.660
So let me explain a bit.

00:22:15.660 --> 00:22:17.710
So, as you all know,
Google Drive is a

00:22:17.710 --> 00:22:19.500
user-managed cloud storage.

00:22:19.500 --> 00:22:22.570
That would typically mean that
the user has total control

00:22:22.570 --> 00:22:25.670
over the files that are
in his Google Drive.

00:22:25.670 --> 00:22:29.430
He could go ahead and read any
of the files, delete or modify

00:22:29.430 --> 00:22:31.320
any of the files in his drive.

00:22:35.150 --> 00:22:38.030
It's not always the best.

00:22:38.030 --> 00:22:39.750
It's not always working
for every use case.

00:22:39.750 --> 00:22:42.320
Let's say you have a web
application and you'd like to

00:22:42.320 --> 00:22:44.770
write a configuration file
to Google Drive.

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:47.950
Well, you wouldn't really want
the user to go ahead and mess

00:22:47.950 --> 00:22:49.040
up that configuration file.

00:22:49.040 --> 00:22:54.160
Maybe that would make your
application have some issues

00:22:54.160 --> 00:22:55.150
when it loads.

00:22:55.150 --> 00:22:57.690
And probably the user doesn't
even want to see that file in

00:22:57.690 --> 00:22:58.490
the first place.

00:22:58.490 --> 00:23:00.750
He's going to be like, what the
hell is this configuration

00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:01.670
file again?

00:23:01.670 --> 00:23:03.790
I haven't created that.

00:23:03.790 --> 00:23:07.170
Same goes for a web-based
game, for example.

00:23:07.170 --> 00:23:10.980
What if a game would want
to Save Game State

00:23:10.980 --> 00:23:12.420
to the user's drive.

00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:15.550
You wouldn't really want to be
the user to be able to go and

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:17.950
potentially change what's
inside that

00:23:17.950 --> 00:23:19.030
Save Game State, right?

00:23:19.030 --> 00:23:21.980
The user could go in and like,
change his gold coins for

00:23:21.980 --> 00:23:23.660
something, and cheat,
basically.

00:23:23.660 --> 00:23:27.540
So it's not always working for
every use case to give total

00:23:27.540 --> 00:23:31.310
control to the user.

00:23:31.310 --> 00:23:33.920
To mitigate this, we launched
a couple features.

00:23:33.920 --> 00:23:37.010
The first one is called
the App Data folder.

00:23:37.010 --> 00:23:41.070
The App Data folder is basically
a hidden folder that

00:23:41.070 --> 00:23:43.900
is only accessible to
your application.

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:45.520
It's really private
to your app.

00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:46.710
The user doesn't even see it.

00:23:46.710 --> 00:23:48.310
It's really hidden.

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:50.670
So that really means that the
user cannot see what's inside

00:23:50.670 --> 00:23:54.750
that folder, cannot read the
files, cannot go in and modify

00:23:54.750 --> 00:23:56.380
these files.

00:23:56.380 --> 00:24:01.330
The only thing that the user can
actually see is the amount

00:24:01.330 --> 00:24:03.380
of data that your application
is using.

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:06.600
And he sees that inside the
Manage Apps dialog, as you can

00:24:06.600 --> 00:24:09.630
see here on the screen,
as an example.

00:24:09.630 --> 00:24:13.280
Also, the only action that a
user can take is to wipe

00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:14.510
entirely the data.

00:24:14.510 --> 00:24:17.560
So he can just basically reset
the data for an app.

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:19.710
Or he could also uninstall
the app.

00:24:19.710 --> 00:24:22.420
That would also wipe
the folder.

00:24:22.420 --> 00:24:25.930
So that's the App Data folder.

00:24:25.930 --> 00:24:27.960
Oh, and by the way,
in Ali's talk--

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:30.380
that's today at 4:25 PM--

