For example, to save
the state of your

00:24:43.170 --> 00:24:44.510
Android app across devices.

00:24:44.510 --> 00:24:48.610
That's really something that
developers have wanted to do

00:24:48.610 --> 00:24:51.820
for a long time, save
the state of

00:24:51.820 --> 00:24:54.180
your app across devices.

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:56.040
You can now do that
through Drive with

00:24:56.040 --> 00:24:56.780
the App Data folder.

00:24:56.780 --> 00:24:59.620
So if you're interested, you
should really show up at Ali's

00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:02.560
talk today.

00:25:02.560 --> 00:25:06.130
The second feature that allows
your application to write

00:25:06.130 --> 00:25:08.910
basically app that they control
is called the Custom

00:25:08.910 --> 00:25:09.780
File Properties.

00:25:09.780 --> 00:25:15.550
So Custom File Properties is
basically a way for you to

00:25:15.550 --> 00:25:18.240
attach metadata to a file
itself in Google Drive.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:25.340
There's an option to actually
make that metadata private to

00:25:25.340 --> 00:25:27.650
your app so that only your app
can read it and access

00:25:27.650 --> 00:25:30.030
it and modify it.

00:25:30.030 --> 00:25:34.690
That's actually great for the
use cases where you would

00:25:34.690 --> 00:25:38.360
actually have to keep, for
example, a folder or files in

00:25:38.360 --> 00:25:40.890
sync with your own system.

00:25:40.890 --> 00:25:44.310
You could actually write, for
example, the ID of the file in

00:25:44.310 --> 00:25:47.090
your own system and directly
attach that to the

00:25:47.090 --> 00:25:50.170
application, make that private
so nobody else can modify it

00:25:50.170 --> 00:25:52.470
or read it.

00:25:52.470 --> 00:25:55.910
Basically, just like you were
attaching a foreign key to a

00:25:55.910 --> 00:25:58.130
Google Drive file.

00:25:58.130 --> 00:25:59.740
That's called Custom
File Properties.

00:26:03.790 --> 00:26:06.570
That was actually all of the
